prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: COSMOS SMGs: mm imaging
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: We aim to obtain mm continuum observations of a sample of 129 SMGs in the COSMOS field. For this we use a single frequency setup with 7.5 GHz total bandwidth and using he coarsest channel resolution. We aim to obtain resolutions of 1" to dissentangle multiple clustered sources.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
** Technical Considerations **
We propose to perform ~240 GHz continuum observations of 129 SMGs (S_1.1mm = 3.9 to 13 mJy; S/N>=4.0) in the COSMOS field (LST~10 hr), drawn from the AzTEC/ASTE 1.1 mm COSMOS survey.
- Frequency:
We chose to perform Band-6 observations since this is the same frequency in which our target SMGs were discovered, making the comparison straightforward.
- Resolution and largest angular scale:
A resolution of 1.0" is sufficient to detect our sources without resolving them, while allowing to disentangle multiple systems (Younger et al. 2007; Tacconi et al. 2008, Aravena et al. 2010; Smolcic et al. 2011, 2012a,b).
Thus, we ask for observations in the C34-2 (0.9") array configuration, albeit observing in the C34-1 configuration would still allow us to complete our goals.
The primary beam of 26" at 240 GHz is large enough to cover the AzTEC sources given the chosen bolometer S/N limit.
The astrometric accuracy of the AzTEC/ASTE data is better than 3" (Aretxaga et al.2011) and several authors find an average offset between bolometer sources and (sub)mm interferometric detections of <5" (all lie within 14").
Note also that artificial source tests on the AzTEC/ASTE map yield that down to S/N=4.0 the probability for an offset >15" between the simulated and the recovered source is negligible (see Fig.6 in Aretxaga et al. 2011).
- Sensitivity:
The fluxes at 1mm for our targets sources range from 3.9 mJy to 13.0 mJy.
Past interferometric observations show that up to 40% of the single-dish detected SMGs may be composed of multiple sources (Smolcic et al. 2012a; Hodge et al. 2013).
Thus we require a high S/N in order to properly address the multiplicity of the bolometer-detected SMGs.
An rms of 0.15 mJy will allow us to detect our faintest sources at 7-sigma, even if they break up into 4 components.
Note that such high S/N and resolution are essential to confirm, and test the multiplicity of the sources, as well as the relative offsets between the dust (mm) and the rest-frame UV to stellar emission from the sources.
With our current tuning, this can be achieved in an integration time of ~1-2 min per source.
- Bandwidth
Since we are interested mostly in pinpointing the location and counterparts of our targets through the mm continuum emission, we ask for the lowest-resolution spectral mode with a total bandwidth of 7.5 GHz.
We ask to not collapse the data cubes to retain the information necessary for searches for serendipituous line emission in our galaxies.
ALMA is the only instrument available for this project as observations of such a large sample would require more than 100 times more observing time with other interferometers (PdBI/CARMA/SMA), making such a project unfeasible.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Submillimeter galaxies (SMGs) are dusty star-forming galaxies at high-z that directly trace the most intense episodes of stellar mass build-up in massive galaxies. Despite the large progress in understanding their properties, all we currently know about SMGs is severely affected by the biases imposed by the traditional radio/IR counterpart identification methods. We propose to perform ALMA 1.2 mm continuum imaging of a complete, flux-limited sample of 129 SMGs in the COSMOS field. These observations will allow us to find unambiguous counterparts and thus perform a critical, unbiased analysis of the SMG properties. Taking advantage of the unprecedented multi-wavelength and photometric redshift coverage of the COSMOS field, this will provide a legacy sample to study the cosmic evolution, dust properties, masses and environments of SMGs. Most importantly, we will quantify the intrinsic redshift distribution, providing a conclusive measurement to the abundance of SMGs at z>4. Finally, this study will illuminate the homogeneity or diversity of the SMG population, possibly changing our view of their evolution and role in the formation of massive ellipticals.
